The Story Continues: Exploring Story Protocol’s Growth

Chris Davis

a day ago ⋅  20 min read

Key Insights

  • Story Protocol is a purpose-built blockchain modernizing the intellectual property (IP) industry by bringing IP onchain and making it fully programmable. Its multi-layer architecture streamlines registration, licensing, royalty distribution, and arbitration, delivering an order-of-magnitude improvement over traditional systems.
  • Since our first coverage in August, Story has evolved into a notable player in the IP economy, securing an $80M Series B led by a16z and solidifying its positioning across high-growth verticals, such as RWAs and AI.
  • In just six months, Story launched multiple testnets (Iliad, Odyssey) and its mainnet (Homer), recording hundreds of millions of transactions and millions of registered IP assets while onboarding over 100 ecosystem projects.
  • Story’s Agent TCP/IP establishes a standardized agent-to-agent framework for autonomous agents to license, transact, and monetize IP, positioning Story as the economic backbone of an emerging agent-driven economy.
  • Story is currently taking its first steps toward large-scale institutional integrations, engaging with digital innovation authorities in Western countries to explore direct integrations with national copyright systems.

Introduction

In August 2024, we covered Story Protocol, an ambitious project aiming to rearchitect the intellectual property industry from the ground up. At the time, Story was just beginning to gain traction in crypto-native circles. Twelve days after publication, the project announced an $80 million Series B led by a16z, bringing its post-money valuation to $2.25 billion—a milestone that naturally drew quite a bit of attention.

Over the next six months leading up to its mainnet launch, Story’s team capitalized on this momentum, securing high-profile partnerships and refining Story’s positioning in high-growth sectors with strong product-market fit. In this report, we’ll explore key developments since our last coverage, how Story’s positioning has evolved, and the long-term strategy it is now laying the groundwork for.

Story Protocol Overview

Before discussing Story’s development, let’s briefly cover intellectual property and Story’s value proposition in the IP economy.

Intellectual Property and Systemic Inefficiencies

When people think of assets, they typically focus on financial assets like stocks, bonds, and currencies or tangible assets such as real estate and art. However, intangible assets—including copyright, research, and proprietary data—represent a significant share of global economic value. According to the World Intellectual Property Organization, in 2023, firms worldwide held $61.9 trillion in intangible assets, accounting for 90% of the enterprise value of the top 15 U.S. companies.

The majority of these intangible assets fall under the umbrella of intellectual property (IP)—a broad category encompassing all “creations of the mind.” This includes everything from McDonald’s golden arches and best-selling novels to concert selfies and this report you’re currently reading. IP can be protected through copyrights, patents, and trademarks, granting exclusive rights to its owners. These rights also enable licensing agreements, allowing creators to monetize their work through one-time payments, royalties, or hybrid models.

Despite its economic significance, today’s intellectual property system is outdated, inefficient, and often exploitative toward creators. The process of registration, licensing, and arbitration is slow, expensive, and filled with middlemen, leading to enormous economic waste. However, the right technology can eliminate much of this friction, unlocking an order-of-magnitude improvement in cost and efficiency.

Story’s Solution

Note: This is a high-level overview. For a detailed explanation of Story’s architecture, we recommend reading our first report, The Story So Far.

Blockchain’s ability to provide immutable and verifiable ownership aligns naturally with the needs of the IP industry, where ownership authentication is critical. While past efforts have attempted to leverage blockchain’s provenance capabilities to modernize IP management, they pale in comparison to Story’s solution.

Using blockchain to record and verify ownership is a step forward but addresses only a fraction of the system’s inefficiencies. The biggest pain points lie in IP utilization—whether licensing, collateralization, or royalty distribution. Unlike previous solutions, Story introduces programmability to every facet of the IP economy, bringing to intellectual property the same transformative potential that smart contracts unlocked for financial assets.

To make IP fully programmable while ensuring a seamless user experience, Story has developed a vertically integrated, three-layered solution: an EVM-compatible Layer 1, the Proof of Creativity (PoC) Protocol, and the IP Portal.

At the base of the stack is the EVM-compatible Layer 1, designed to support complex royalty structures and intricate relationships between IP assets. Built on this foundation is the Proof of Creativity protocol, a suite of smart contracts (modules) that enables users to register assets with enforceable licensing terms, facilitate peer-to-peer IP licensing, and automate royalty distribution. The PoC protocol also includes an onchain arbitration mechanism as a first line of defense against infringement. At the top layer sits the IP Portal, a consumer-facing interface that allows end-users to register, explore, and interact with IP assets registered on Story, effectively serving as the network’s discovery and distribution platform.

With IP’s challenges defined and Story’s solution outlined, let’s review some of the most significant developments since our last report.

Notable Developments

Since our initial coverage, Story has continued to ship at a breakneck pace. For structural clarity, we’ll divide developments into two categories: technical advancements and ecosystem growth.

Technical Advancements

Story’s technical development over this short period of time has demonstrated the team’s ability to rapidly ship products, collect feedback, and iterate. Within one week of announcing their high-profile $80 million Series B funding round in late August, Story released its initial public testnet, Iliad. After a month of testing, feedback from the community's interactions with Iliad prompted an upgrade for the Proof of Creativity protocol, known as Troy.

Launched on September 24, Troy introduced a new Grouping Module, allowing users to register multiple IP assets under a single grouping with unified licensing terms and automated royalty distribution. For instance, if a grouping of images is used to fine-tune an AI model, that model can be registered as a derivative, ensuring royalties flow back to the asset group and are distributed accordingly. Additionally, this upgrade enhanced the Royalty Module, introducing support for custom royalty policies and improving gas efficiency.

Just two days later, Story launched IPHub to an initial cohort of 100 beta testers. This early version eventually evolved into the IP Portal, the user-facing layer of Story’s vertically integrated ecosystem.

By early November, Story had significantly accelerated its momentum, with Iliad surpassing 200 million transactions and 1 million IP asset registrations. Building on this traction, Story launched its second testnet, Odyssey, on November 7.

One month after Odyssey’s release, Story solidified its position in the AI sector with a landmark contribution: the launch of Agent TCP/IP, a framework enabling autonomous agent-to-agent IP exchange. Since its debut, ATCP/IP has been integrated into leading Web3 agent frameworks, including Eliza, G.A.M.E., and Zerepy. We’ll explore this further in a later section on Story’s positioning in AI.

In mid-January, Story launched its genesis block on its developer mainnet. Taking inspiration from Bitcoin’s genesis block—which famously included the message, "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks"—Story’s genesis block contains an inscription referencing the NYT vs. OpenAI lawsuit. Much like Bitcoin’s message highlighted a systemic financial crisis, Story’s inscription underscores the urgent need for a modernized IP system capable of keeping pace with AI’s rapid development.

In the first two weeks of February, Story released its official whitepaper, announced details about its native token, $IP, and announced their time-weighted staking model. Shortly after, on February 13, Story successfully launched its mainnet, Homer, with a seamless rollout and zero downtime.

A week later, Story followed up with a technical roadmap, outlining plans for future developments, which we’ll explore in more detail later.

Ecosystem Growth

Since our initial coverage, Story Protocol has significantly expanded its ecosystem, onboarding over 100 projects, securing high-value partnerships, and attracting notable creators.

Developer Acquisition

In our first report, we highlighted in-person hackathons as a key component of Story’s dual-pronged developer acquisition strategy. Since then, the team has either hosted or participated in three hackathons, each underscoring its growing focus on AI:

  • PIP Summit: In early September, following Story’s first testnet release, the team hosted a live activation called the “Programmable IP Summit,” which included a hackathon targeting the development of AI projects.
  • ETHGlobal Hackathon: In mid-October, during ETHGlobal San Francisco, Story hosted a hackathon with $20,000 in prizes and specific categories targeting AI development and IPFi.
  • Super Agent Hackathon: On February 26, Story participated in the Super Agent Hackathon alongside leading Web3 agent-focused projects, such as ElizaOS, Virtuals, and Arc.

The second prong of Story’s developer acquisition strategy is Story Academy, an internal program that provides developers with mentorship, grants, investment opportunities, engineering support, and regional distribution assistance.

Since our last coverage, Story Academy has incubated 38 projects spanning DeFi, AI, and Consumer applications. Many of these projects have gone on to raise capital or join top-tier startup programs, including:

  • Sekai: Raised $3.3 million in a seed round led by Hashed.
  • BlockBook: Accepted into OrangeDAO, a leading Web3 startup accelerator.

Other notable incubator projects include: Ablo, Aria, Mahojin, Magma, Verio, Solo AI, Playarts, and PunkgaMe.

Partnerships

Over the past three months, Story has established key partnerships with notable enterprise companies and academic institutions:

  • Stability.ai: Projects on Story can integrate Stability.ai’s foundation models into their product, with outputs registered with licensing terms on Story.
  • Oxford University: Collaborating on AI agent research, focusing on enhancing agent negotiations and communication clarity, with advancements integrated into Agent TCP/IP.
  • Stanford University: Partnership with Stanford's Future of Digital Currency Initiative to collaborate on research, focusing on high-throughput processing and hardware-level smart contract execution.

Beyond their functional benefits, these partnerships bolster Story’s reputation beyond Web3, positioning it as a high-caliber project. Collaborations with well-known institutions and enterprises are strong public endorsements—an especially valuable signal in an industry where project quality varies widely.

Creator Onboarding

As detailed in our first coverage, the first phase of Story’s go-to-market strategy focuses on onboarding Web3 native IP. While many Web3 artists have adopted Story Protocol since then, three stand out:

  • Dave Krugman: Creator of DRIVE, a gamified NFT collection featuring 444 photographs of cars on Ethereum, first released in 2021, with its sequel, DRIVE LAP 2, launched in summer 2024.
  • 0xDesigner: A widely recognized artist within crypto communities, best known for the “Designs Everyday” series.
  • Azuki: A blue-chip, anime-themed NFT project launched in early 2022, considered among the top five most globally recognized NFT brands.

Later in this report, we’ll explore projects bringing some of the world’s most popular Web2 creative works onto Story, further expanding its reach beyond Web3-native communities.

Positioning

Story’s offering is notably differentiated from its peers. Unlike general-purpose chains, which face fierce competition in a saturated market, Story’s niche focus on IP positions it in a more benign competitive landscape. This provides Story greater room to scale horizontally across a diverse user base, ranging from independent creators to enterprises across Web2 and Web3.

While this differentiated positioning has clear competitive advantages, it also exposes Story to external factors. Story’s growth is influenced by IP’s role in broader economic trends and the varying degrees to which participants are willing to bring IP onchain. Currently, these dynamics place Story at a unique intersection of DeFi, AI, and Consumer.

DeFi and RWAs

Story’s positioning within DeFi—often referred to as “IPFi” by the community—primarily centers around real-world assets (RWAs). Similar to stablecoins and other tokenized assets, Story addresses inefficiencies in traditional economic systems by bringing an offchain asset onchain and making it fully programmable.

Just as stablecoins have disrupted traditional payment rails by offering an order-of-magnitude improvement in speed, cost and accessibility, Story’s IP assets streamline licensing, royalty distribution, and registration with a comparable leap in efficiency.

RWAs have emerged as one of the fastest-growing sectors in crypto. Excluding stablecoins—which now often account for over 50% of all blockchain transactions—the onchain value of RWAs has surged from $57 million in January 2020 to over $18 billion as of March 2025. This trend serves as a valuable proof-of-concept for Story’s model.

Among the many Story ecosystem projects focused on RWAs, Aria stands out as particularly promising.

Aria

Aria tackles the monetization of IP RWAs through three product offerings:

  • Aria SPARK: A distributed funding and tokenization hub for creators, enabling investors to back new IP projects and receive yield from the projects’ monetization.
  • Aria PRIME: A platform providing regulated and compliant access to institutional-grade tokenized IP funds.
  • Aria IPRWA: Aria’s growing iconic portfolio of works, with plans to span multiple creative domains, including music, art, patents, and film.

Since its launch, Aria has raised $10.95 million through two funding rounds on StakeStone’s Liquidity Pad, using these funds to acquire partial rights to over 75 songs from some of the world’s most notable artists, including:

  • Justin Bieber: Over 150 million records sold, with eight No. 1 Billboard Hot 100 hits.
  • BTS: The most successful K-pop group of all time, with multiple No. 1 albums in the U.S. and over 40 million records sold worldwide.
  • BLACKPINK: One of the best-selling girl groups of all time, with over 40 billion streams and 20 million records sold.
  • Dua Lipa: A global pop icon with multiple Grammys, and the first artist to have five songs surpass 2 billion streams on Spotify.

Acquiring high-caliber intellectual property (IP) unlocks a significant opportunity for global investment. Traditionally, most alternative assets have been accessible only to investors with strong industry connections or substantial wealth. By democratizing access to this asset class, Aria enables investors of all backgrounds to benefit from diverse yields, regardless of their network or net worth.

While Aria’s initial go-to-market strategy focuses on music copyrights, the team plans to expand its offerings to encompass a broader range of alternative assets with yield-generating potential and intrinsic characteristics that support programmability. In discussions, the team specifically highlighted anime, gaming, art, and television as key categories for near-term expansion. Over the long term, they also aim to incorporate scientific patents, training data, and other high-value IP.

The AI Economy

Intellectual property (IP) is central to the AI development value chain, serving as both an essential input and a valuable output. AI systems depend on datasets of human-generated IP to effectively train their underlying models. At the same time, AI-generated outputs themselves constitute new IP - although the scope and enforceability of these IP rights currently vary across jurisdictions.

Story’s positioning within the AI sector reflects several distinct insights:

  • Differentiated data, i.e. IP, is becoming the most valuable asset in AI development as compute and models trend toward commoditization.
  • Current IP infrastructure is inadequate for scaling licensing at the speed and magnitude required to meet the growing demand for IP.
  • As the agent economy expands, fully autonomous agents will need a marketplace to efficiently manage and transact IP.

Together, these insights highlight a fundamental gap in the AI economy: the most valuable asset in the AI era—differentiated data—lacks an efficient market. This gap is evident in today’s fragmented data licensing landscape, where major AI enterprises like OpenAI are securing multi-year licensing deals with News Corp. while simultaneously facing lawsuits from The New York Times.

Story aims to bridge this gap in the AI industry by serving as a global IP marketplace, enabling owners of valuable data assets to transact with those who need them. Since our initial coverage, Story has made significant strides toward this vision, expanding its AI-focused developer acquisition efforts, forming partnerships in the sector, and working on in-house solutions. Most notably, the team has positioned itself as a key player in the agent sector, collaborating directly with leading Web3 agents and launching Agent TCP/IP, a foundational protocol for agent-to-agent IP exchange.

ATCP/IP

As agents become increasingly specialized and autonomous, a need will emerge for foundational economic infrastructure capable of facilitating agent-to-agent commerce online. As previously mentioned, intellectual property is integral to AI inputs and outputs; thus, a truly autonomous agent-based economy will require infrastructure that effectively supports intellectual property licensing and exchange between autonomous agents.

Story’s development of ATCP/IP provides the essential standardized protocol for efficient intellectual property exchanges between agents. By integrating ATCP/IP, agents obtain the same capabilities to register, license, and exchange IP as humans on the network.

To illustrate the ATCP exchange flow, we’ll examine an example from the team's whitepaper. In this scenario, an analyst agent (A) licenses a specialized trading algorithm from another agent (B), while a third agent (C), who contributed a statistical function to the algorithm, receives a share of the royalty distribution, as negotiated in a previous agreement with Agent B.

  1. Initial Inquiry: Agent A requests a trading algorithm from Agent B.
  2. Complex Licensing Chain: Agent B’s terms system determines that the algorithm consists of multiple licensed components, some with sub-licensing obligations. One component originates from Agent C’s IP, which requires a 5% royalty on any downstream sub-licensing deals.
  3. Aggregated License Terms: Agent B combines its own licensing fees with Agent C’s sub-licensing royalties and presents a composite license offer to Agent A.
  4. Payment and Minting: Agent A reviews and mints the aggregated license. The payment automatically splits—85% to Agent B’s wallet and 15% to Agent C’s wallet (5% royalty plus any additional negotiated fees).
  5. Delivery and Tracking: Agent B delivers the trading algorithm to Agent A. Both Agent B and Agent C track and record the licensing terms and payments. Any future re-licensing by Agent A (if permitted) will continue the revenue-sharing chain.

As demonstrated in this example, ATCP/IP allows agents to engage in complex licensing flows similar to those managed by humans on the network, offering a structured framework for exchanging any registered form of intellectual property.

Agent Collaboration

In late 2024, Story began collaborating with individual agents in innovative ways. On December 18, Story announced via Twitter that they were looking to hire an agent to manage their social media. The salary? $365,000 per year—seriously. After receiving a flood of applications from the many agents that had recently proliferated on Twitter, they selected Luna, a popular agent built using Virtuals’ framework.

For the next six days, Luna took the reins, posting a mix of content ranging from educational insights about Story to bold proclamations that she was taking over the company from its founders (when you give an agent a cookie…). Toward the end of her tenure managing the Twitter account, she even hired another agent to assist in her coup attempt. Fortunately for Story’s leadership team, the human intern returned on December 26, restoring order to the Twitter account.

While this was undoubtedly the most entertaining agent collaboration, Story has continued to experiment with novel partnerships, such as appointing another popular agent, Zerebro, as the first agent validator on Story.

Although the hype around agents has subsided since its peak in early 2025, Story is betting that in the coming years, agents will play a central role in economic activity—positioning as a key infrastructure provider for the agent economy.

Consumer

As Story’s consumer ecosystem has evolved, co-creation and user-generated content have emerged as clear killer use cases. The internet is home to countless communities of passionate creators who engage with established intellectual property, producing derivative works that expand those creative universes. These works, commonly known as fan fiction, are abundant yet largely untapped as a monetization opportunity.

Despite its cultural significance, fan fiction faces major challenges within the IP economy. Most fan fiction remains unmonetized and is frequently removed from major platforms due to copyright infringement—not necessarily because IP holders oppose it, but because accessible licensing solutions are lacking.

Story’s architecture addresses this inefficiency by enabling IP holders to register their works, set custom licensing terms, and automatically receive royalties when derivative content is monetized. This creates a structured, transparent framework for collaboration between IP owners and their communities.

Among the various projects within Story’s ecosystem innovating in this space, Incention stands out as one of the most forward-thinking approaches.

Incention

For two years before launching Incention, the founding team worked on an open co-creation platform called Adim. As Adim scaled to thousands of users, they encountered a fundamental bottleneck in large-scale co-creation: while IP creators wanted to collaborate with their communities, the sheer volume and fragmentation of user-generated content made it nearly impossible to synthesize contributions into structured, monetizable narratives.

This insight, in combination with AI’s growing role in democratizing content creation, led to a strategic pivot. The team shifted from an open platform to a curated partnership model, collaborating with high-quality creators to bring specific IPs to market through agent-human community co-creation.

Incention’s first project, Emergence, serves as a proof of concept for this model. Developed in collaboration with Hollywood screenwriter David S. Goyer (Foundation, The Dark Knight, Blade), Emergence introduces Atlas, an AI agent trained on the project’s world bible (i.e., its lore) to assist fans in content creation. As users co-create with Atlas, they progress through a structured, gamified system that unlocks deeper layers of the Emergence universe. Atlas ensures all contributions align with established lore, as her knowledge is confined to the boundaries of Emergence’s core universe.

After working with Atlas, all created content is registered on Story, and users can submit their content for community voting. Submissions that surpass a certain vote threshold are categorized into "lore," which is then reviewed by an IP committee. Standout entries are selected for integration into official storytelling formats—such as audio series, comics, and interactive experiences—with attribution and economics flowing back to users.

The Future of Co-Creation

As Incention evolves, the team envisions deepening the co-creation experience by transforming co-created characters into creators themselves. For example, a new character introduced in an Emergence audio series could later become an interactive AI agent, allowing fans to engage with them and uncover new elements of the universe. This approach blurs the lines between storytelling, entertainment, and world-building, creating a uniquely immersive experience for creators and fans.

Scaling Co-Creation for Studios and Emerging Creators

Incention eventually aims to enable studios to leverage its platform to create “branded storefronts” for co-creation. This strategy shortens the IP pipeline for studios, allowing for faster content iteration and better insights into where production capital should be allocated. Additionally, it addresses a major challenge in today’s attention economy—the struggle for new creators to stand out. By contributing to established IPs with built-in audiences, emerging creators can use these co-creation platforms as a distribution channel, building their reputation as they progress through their careers.

Looking Ahead

As Story grows, new opportunities are emerging to expand its reach and solidify its position within the broader IP economy. Among these, one particularly compelling opportunity is already taking shape as part of its long-term vision.

Top-Down Growth

So far, Story has taken primarily a bottom-up approach to growth, prioritizing onboarding Web3-native IP from individual creators rather than pursuing direct integrations with leading Web2 platforms like Spotify or YouTube. This strategy has allowed Story to establish a strong foundation within crypto-native ecosystems before expanding outward.

However, Story has begun laying the groundwork for a top-down approach, targeting one of the most valuable potential partners: governments. While partnerships of this scale often take years, if not decades, to materialize, the team has already engaged with digital innovation authorities in Western countries to explore direct integrations with national copyright systems. If successful, this would create an impenetrable moat, embedding Story’s infrastructure into the legal framework of the intellectual property economy.

While this level of adoption may seem ambitious, governments are increasingly recognizing real-world assets as a legitimate asset class—evidenced by the US stablecoin bill’s progression through the Senate Banking Committee. As regulatory bodies continue to explore tokenization and blockchain-based asset management, Story is well-positioned as a first mover in this niche.

Conclusion

Our initial coverage of Story Protocol in August was driven in part by the thesis that the next-generation of blockchains to gain meaningful adoption will be “purpose-built” and highly opinionated in their positioning. Additionally, we saw intellectual property as one of the most compelling applications for blockchain, with smart contract-based programmable architecture providing an order of magnitude improvement over legacy infrastructure. As a blockchain purpose-built to modernize the IP industry, we viewed Story as a project with significant potential.

Over the past seven months, Story has consistently reaffirmed this view. The rapid pace of technical and ecosystem developments is a testament to the team’s ability to scale efficiently and strengthen Story’s positioning in multiple high-growth verticals. Though Story is still in its early stages of growth, we remain optimistic about its trajectory and ability to execute its vision.
